Taiwan Stocks: China Steel, Nan Kang Rubber Tire, Wintek Corp.

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-02-23T01:54:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-23/asustek-computer-china-steel-nan-kang-taiwan-stocks-preview.html
Stocks of the following companies
had unusual price changes in Taipei trading. Stock symbols are
in parentheses, and shares are as of 9:48 a.m. local time.  Taiwan’s Taiex Index fell 37.95, or 0.4 percent, to
8,635.72.    China Steel Corp . (2002 TT) gained 1.4 percent to NT$33.65.
Taiwan’s biggest maker of the metal plans to sell global
depositary receipts backed by as many as 840 million shares, the
company said in a statement to the stock exchange yesterday. The
proceeds will be used to improve its financial structure and
boost working capital, the Kaohsiung-based company said.  Nan Kang Rubber Tire Co. (2101 TT) increased 1 percent to
NT$48.05, the highest since Jan. 6. The company plans to buy
back 14.5 million common shares representing 2.14 percent of
outstanding shares at between NT$42 and NT$50 each from Feb. 23
to April 21, the company said in a statement to the stock
exchange yesterday.    Wintek Corp . (2384 TT), which supplies touch sensors to
Apple Inc.’s iPads, dropped 3.5 percent to NT$52.40, the most
since Dec. 29. Workers at a Wintek factory in  China  wrote a
letter to Apple Inc., urging the U.S. company to help address
their grievances over a chemical poisoning they said could harm
their health, Reuters reported, citing the letter. Jay Huang, a
Wintek spokesman, didn’t answer two calls to his office. Jill Tan, an Apple spokeswoman, didn’t answer a call to her Hong Kong
mobile phone.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Weiyi Lim in Singapore at 
